observations.recommendation:
To strengthen the risk management capabilities of the Municipal Government and enable it to manage its vulnerabilities in the event of disruptive events, we recommended that the LCE institutionalize the Public Service Continuity Plan (PSCP) by creating a working group that will perform the following activities:

to conduct risk assessment; 

to identify critical processes and functions; 

to determine scenarios that may disrupt normal operation; 

to conduct risk analysis and impact analysis; 

to formulate the PSCP based on the identified risks on critical processes and functions and its related steps to be followed to eliminate, if not mitigate, the impact of the determined disruptions following the prescribed template and be guided by the PSCP guidebook; and

to submit plan to the MDRRMO for review, to the LCE for approval, and to the Sangguniang Bayan for the passage of a resolution to institutionalize the PSCP.

We also recommended Management to improve their monitoring of operational requirements like the submission of PSCP.

We recommended that the department heads concerned shall:
at the beginning of the year, submit to the Municipal Mayor a list of all-ongoing government PPAs and those that are to be implemented during the year;
within ten (10) days after the award of the infrastructure project or before the start of the program/activity, communicate to the Municipal Mayor that the appropriate project signboards and/or public notices are already posted;
submit to the Municipal Mayor, Quarterly Report on Government Projects/Programs/Activities at last day of the end of the quarter, supported with pictures of tarpaulin and the PPAs.
Further, we recommend that the Municipal Mayor designate a staff of the Mayor’s Office to consolidate the reports mentioned in Sections 1.7.1 and 1.7.3 submitted by various department heads, and submit the same to the Audit Team, within the reglementary period.
Moreover, we recommend that the Municipal Mayor inform the Audit Team within ten (10) days after the award of the infrastructure project or before the start of the program/activity, that the appropriate project signboards and/or public notices are already posted, based on the submitted report of the department heads concerned.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor, through the SWM – Focal Person should:
prepare the necessary documents required for incorporations to the Municipality’s SWM Plan so as to obtain the NSWMC’s approval;

strictly enforce existing laws and ordinances on proper solid waste management;

incorporate in the SWM Plan the conduct of necessary training for SWM personnel to ensure that solid wastes are properly handled and that the risk of hazards to them and to the public are avoided or minimized;

provide complete personal protective equipment and paraphernalia to protect the garbage collectors and other SWM personnel from the hazards of handling solid wastes;

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor direct:

the Municipal Accountant and Municipal Treasurer  to reconcile their respective records and make the necessary adjustments in the books to come up with accurate and reliable balances of RPT and SET Receivables accounts and support the  respective accounts with subsidiary records based on the certified list of taxpayers submitted by the Municipal Treasurer;

the Municipal Treasurer and the Municipal Assessor to continue their coordination on the issue of double assessment of  real property as reported  by the taxpayers until such time that the  conduct  of comprehensive tax mapping operation to establish a complete inventory of all real properties  and to identify the ownership of every piece of real property in undertaken. | We recommended that the Municipal Mayor direct:

the Municipal Accountant and Municipal Treasurer  to reconcile their respective records and make the necessary adjustments in the books to come up with accurate and reliable balances of RPT and SET Receivables accounts and support the  respective accounts with subsidiary records based on the certified list of taxpayers submitted by the Municipal Treasurer;

the Municipal Treasurer and the Municipal Assessor to continue their coordination on the issue of double assessment of  real property as reported  by the taxpayers until such time that the  conduct  of comprehensive tax mapping operation to establish a complete inventory of all real properties  and to identify the ownership of every piece of real property in undertaken.

We recommended that the Municipal  Mayor  advise:
the Municipal Accountant and the Designated Property Custodian to record the seven road lots under the  Infrastructure Assets - Road Network (1-07-03-010) account pursuant to COA Circular No. 2015-008 in the books of accounts  and the RPCPPE, respectively;
the Municipal Accountant to provide the Municipal Assessor and Municipal Treasurer with copies of Deeds of Absolute  Sale of each  lot for recording purposes;
the Municipal Assessor  to facilitate the transfer   and ensure Titles to all  road lots are in the name  of the Municipal Government of Indang   to establish the Municipality’s  absolute ownership thereof.
